Comment: I've never tried this opening before. I don't like the look of it. Please tell me what is.
I start my favorite opening which is the king's pawn opening.
He prevents me from getting my queens' pawn into the battle.
I always try to develop my pieces early.
Finally, he returned the king's pawn opening.
I develop my other knight.
He frees his dark-square bishop, but traps the white.
I will take advantage of the fact there is no pawn to stop me.
He blocks it with his bishop.
A fair trade.
He takes with his knight which is what I would've done.
I free my light-square bishop.
I really don't know why he does that.
I castle.
Now I really don't understand.
I try to get my knight more into the battle.
Now I think I see his plan. My guess is that The queen will somehow come down and try to checkmate  me protected by the rook.
I take the free pawn.
Maybe that bishop has something to do with the checkmate too.
I honestly don't know why I did that.
